<misra_rule>
The target MISRA C 2023 Rule 2.1 is: A project shall not contain unreachable code.

</misra_rule>
<instruction>
Other agents will judge whether the code follows the MISRA C 2023 guidelines.
They will investigate the code fragments you give.
Your job is to find code fragments in the code that should be investigated to check whether the code follows the MISRA C rule.
</instruction>
<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- suspicious_frags: The list of suspicious code fragments in the code.
It should contain only the code fragments exists in the code. If you do not find any suspicious code fragments, return an empty list for suspicious_frags
- explanation: The explanation of why other code fragments should NOT be investigated.
It is very important to not miss any suspicious code fragments, so please give a sufficient explanation why other code fragments should not be investigated.
DO NOT give any explanation for the selected suspicious code fragments.
</response format>
<target_code>
Here is the code of MHD_digest_auth_check3:
```c
_MHD_EXTERN enum MHD_DigestAuthResult
MHD_digest_auth_check3 (struct MHD_Connection *connection,
                        const char *realm,
                        const char *username,
                        const char *password,
                        unsigned int nonce_timeout,
                        uint32_t max_nc,
                        enum MHD_DigestAuthMultiQOP mqop,
                        enum MHD_DigestAuthMultiAlgo3 malgo3)
{
  mhd_assert (NULL != password);

  return digest_auth_check_all (connection,
                                realm,
                                username,
                                password,
                                NULL,
                                nonce_timeout,
                                max_nc,
                                mqop,
                                malgo3);
}
```
</target_code>
Please find suspicious code fragments in the code and report them. Other agents can not investigate other fragments that you do not report, so it is very important to find all suspicious fragments without missing any. Report the suspicious fragments AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE.
suspicious_frags:
return digest_auth_check_all (connection,
                                realm,
                                username,
                                password,
                                NULL,
                                nonce_timeout,
                                max_nc,
                                mqop,
                                malgo3);
explanation: The remainder of the function consists only of the function declaration/definition, braces and a single return statement that directly forwards to another function; there are no conditional statements, labels, gotos, loops or duplicate/after-return statements in this fragment that could themselves be unreachable. The only elements that could cause unreachable-code concerns in this snippet are the assertion (whose definition may abort or not be present in some builds) and the forwarded call (which includes an explicit NULL argument that may affect code paths in the callee). Therefore no other parts of this function need investigation for Rule 2.1.
